<HEADLINE>
<P>
PETITIONS SUBMITTED FOR OREGON GAY RIGHTS BAN; ELECTIONS: BACKERS HOPE TO 
QUALIFY THE INITIATIVE ON THE NOVEMBER BALLOT. MEANWHILE, SIMILAR DRIVES IN 
WASHINGTON STATE AND MISSOURI FAIL. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 An Oregon group that is seeking a ban on gay rights legislation submitted 
signatures Friday in hopes of getting its proposal on the November ballot. 
Groups with similar goals came up short in Washington state and Missouri. 
</P>
<P>
 They are among several states where petition drives by gay rights opponents 
have been under way this year. In Arizona on Thursday, a group sponsoring such 
a drive said it had dropped the petition campaign and instead would concentrate 
on challenging existing gay rights ordinances. 
</P>
<P>
 In Michigan, backers face a Monday deadline of submitting enough signatures to 
force a statewide vote. 
</P>
<P>
 The Oregon Citizens Alliance turned in what it said were 120,000 signatures to 
put its new anti-gay rights initiative on the statewide ballot. The measure 
will qualify for the November ballot if the secretary of state determines that 
at least 89,000 of the signatures are valid. 
</P>
<P>
 Alliance Chairman Lon Mabon said he was confident that the measure would pass 
because the language is less strident than the wording of a similar measure 
defeated by voters in 1992. 
</P>
<P>
 In Missouri, Paul Summers, president of the Amendment Coalition, said his 
group did not get enough signatures by Friday's deadline for a ballot proposal 
to prevent the state and local governments from enacting laws and ordinances 
providing special protection to homosexuals. 
</P>
<P>
 In Washington state, sponsors blamed their failure on gay rights activists who 
stumped the state urging voters not to sign the petitions. 
</P>
<P>
 The group said it collected more than 180,000 signatures, but officials 
recommend submitting at least 210,000 to ensure that the requirement of 181,667 
valid signatures is met. 
</P>
