<P>
WEST VALLEY FOCUS: NORTH HILLS; GROUNDBREAKING TO MARK ANNIVERSARY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By ERIC SLATER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 New Horizons, a nonprofit organization providing housing for mentally retarded 
people in the San Fernando Valley, will celebrate its 40th anniversary today 
with a groundbreaking for two new group homes. 
</P>
<P>
 Supporters of the organization, which currently operates seven homes, will 
gather at the New Horizons headquarters at 15725 Parthenia St. at 5:30 p.m. for 
festivities. 
</P>
<P>
 The evening will serve as a fund-raiser for the planned group homes, group 
spokeswoman Gloria Griskevitch said.  
</P>
<P>
 Construction of the homes -- one at 8733 Haskell Ave. and the other at 15917 
Chase St. -- is scheduled to begin in November, Griskevitch said. Residents 
will be moving in about this time next year. 
</P>
<P>
 Following groundbreaking ceremonies, Assemblyman Richard Katz (D-Sylmar) will 
speak. Afterward, an optional $40-a-plate benefit dinner will be served. ERIC 
SLATER 
</P>
