<HEADLINE>
<P>
WORLD CUP USA '94 / QUARTERFINALS; SPOTLIGHT; IT HAS NO ARMY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By ELLIOTT ALMOND 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Joao Havelange, president of FIFA, said Friday in Dallas that the 
international governing body of soccer can do little to prevent such tragedies 
as the murder of Andres Escobar, the Colombia defender who was shot in Medellin 
last weekend. 
</P>
<P>
 Havelange said nothing could be done by FIFA to stop fanaticism. 
</P>
<P>
 Speaking at his first news conference of World Cup '94, Havelange said FIFA 
made its sentiments known by asking for two minutes of silence before the two 
games on the day of the murder. Escobar was shot for accidentally kicking in an 
own goal during a game against the United States. 
</P>
<P>
 "You cannot expect FIFA to be in every country and legislate what is 
occurring," Havelange said. "You cannot expect FIFA to send troops to try to 
bring about a type of calm to this disorder." 
</P>
<P>
 Sepp Blatter, FIFA general secretary, said it would be impossible for FIFA to 
take any action to quell the emotions of soccer fans. 
</P>
<P>
 "If the United Nations are not able to stop any assassinations, how can FIFA, 
with only its spoken power, stop such cases?" he asked. ELLIOTT ALMOND 
</P>
</TEXT>
