<HEADLINE>
<P>
HUSBAND FACES MURDER CHARGES; CRIME: SPECIAL ALLEGATION COULD MEAN DEATH 
PENALTY FOR MAN WHO CONFESSED TO STABBING WIFE AND MOTHER-IN-LAW, SETTING HOME 
AFIRE. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By RENE LYNCH, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 A Santa Ana man was charged Friday with murder and arson after allegedly 
confessing to killing his estranged wife and her mother in a jealous rage and 
then setting their Anaheim home on fire. 
</P>
<P>
 Tuan Ngoc Le, 32, also faces a so-called special circumstance allegation of 
multiple murders, meaning he could face the death penalty if convicted of 
fatally stabbing Loi Thanh Phan, 30, and her mother, Sao Thi Nguyen, 69. 
</P>
<P>
 Le's arraignment in North Orange County Municipal Court was postponed to Aug. 
12. He is being held in the Orange County Men's Jail without bail. 
</P>
<P>
 Le's court-appointed attorney could not be reached for comment Friday. 
</P>
<P>
 According to relatives, Le had a history of abusing his estranged wife and had 
repeatedly threatened to kill her in the past. He told Orange County Sheriff's 
deputies he killed the women after learning that his wife was car-pooling to 
work with another man, said Sgt. Randy Benicky. 
</P>
<P>
 He told deputies he went to the home Wednesday morning to confront her and 
then used a knife to attack her, Benicky said. 
</P>
<P>
 But relatives question whether Le had planned the attack. They say Le knew 
that the man who was taking Phan to work was a relative and had no reason to be 
jealous. They also say Le's pride was hurt when Phan had found a good-paying 
job with an Anaheim electronics firm, while he had to borrow money to make his 
rent. 
</P>
<P>
 The couple had recently emigrated from Vietnam with their 4-year-old daughter. 
They were experiencing marital problems, but were together over the July 4th 
holiday weekend and were discussing getting back together shortly before the 
slayings took place, relatives said. 
</P>
<P>
 A neighbor who ran to the house when he saw smoke billowing out a window said 
he found Le washing his hands and a knife in the kitchen. The bodies were found 
in the living room, where Le allegedly set afire the carpet and a lawn mower. 
</P>
<P>
 Phan's eldest sister, Lien Thi Phan, 46, suffered smoke inhalation and burns 
to her feet during the ordeal. 
</P>
<P>
 Deputy Dist. Atty. Clyde P. Von Der Ahe said prosecutors will determine 
whether to seek the death penalty against Le. 
</P>
</TEXT>
